            <h1 class="post-title">Running Ghost 0.7.2 on Windows</h1>
            <section class="post-meta">
                <time class="post-date" datetime="2015-12-07">07 December 2015</time>  on <a href="tag/tutorial/index.html">Tutorial</a>
            </section>
        </header>

        <section class="post-content">
            <p>It took me a few hours of tinkering with <em>ghost-0.7.2, node.js, python</em>, and finally <em>buster</em>, but deploying static sites created with ghost on Windows is finally easier.</p>

<p>Since the only way to generate and deploy Ghost's static pages is with <a href="https://github.com/axitkhurana/buster">buster</a>, doing it in Windows 10 is a pain in the ass; buster was not written with Windows users in mind.</p>

<h2 id="downloadingtheinstallers">Downloading the installers</h2>

<p>First you will need the following:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="https://git-for-windows.github.io/">Git Bash</a></li>
<li><a href="https://nodejs.org/download/release/v4.2.0/">node.js</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.python.org/downloads/">Python</a> with version below 3.0</li>
<li>pip - installed with either <a href="https://chocolatey.org/packages/pip">chocolatey</a> or pip 7.1.2 <a href="https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/installing/">here</a></li>
</ul>

<h2 id="theprocess">The Process</h2>

<p>Other people will have various ways of setting up their installation, so be sure to have at least a familiar understanding of command line and command line tools.</p>

<p><strong>Step 1:</strong></p>

<p>For Git Pages projects:</p>

<p>Create a new repository called <strong>blog</strong>, add a branch called <em>"gh-pages"</em>. This will serve as your project page for Git Pages. It will look like <a href="http://username.github.io/blog/">http://username.github.io/blog/</a></p>

<p>Open up git bash and clone your repository:</p>

<pre><code>$ git clone https://github.com/username/blog.git
</code></pre>

<p>Check to see if the installations were successful by typing in your command line:</p>

<pre><code>python --version
</code></pre>

<hr />

<pre><code>node --version
</code></pre>

<hr />

<pre><code>npm --version
</code></pre>

<p>If they output their respective versions, then the installation is complete. </p>

<p>Download <a href="https://ghost.org/download/">Ghost</a> and extract it onto your desktop. Enter the newly created folder and open git bash.</p>

<pre><code>$ npm install
</code></pre>

<p>Let ghost install its packages, this will be in a folder called <em>node_modules</em>.</p>

<pre><code>$ npm start
</code></pre>

<p>A local instance of your site will now be running on <a href="http://localhost:2368">http://localhost:2368</a>. <br />
Now you can play with the settings on <a href="http://localhost:2368/ghost">http://localhost:2368/ghost</a></p>

<h2 id="modifyingbusterforwindows">Modifying Buster for Windows</h2>

<p>Buster is a tool for generating and deploying static pages. It can only be used while you are running a local instance of your site.</p>

<p>Get buster here: <a href="https://github.com/axitkhurana/buster">https://github.com/axitkhurana/buster</a></p>

<h2 id="important">IMPORTANT:</h2>

<p>This build of buster is not compatible with Windows, here is a <em>buster.py</em> file which will fix routing and file name issues you might encounter.</p>

<p><a href="https://github.com/amphipath/buster/blob/d67304251484d148abcceb2018902c6a3f51b322/buster/buster.py">Link to file</a></p>

<p>Copy or download this and replace <em>buster.py</em> inside /buster/buster.</p>

<p><strong>Optional</strong>: </p>

<hr />

<p>If you wish to route your local git repository with buster, change directory into /buster/buster and open up git bash. Type in:</p>

<pre><code>$ python buster.py setup
</code></pre>

<p>Enter your repository's SSH link. It will look like this: git@github.com:username/blog.git</p>

<p>Buster will then create a folder called <em>static</em>.</p>

<hr />

<p>If you do not with to do this for reasons like missing dependencies or broken links, then follow the next step.</p>

<p>Make sure you have your local site up and running. Enter /buster/buster, open git bash and type in:</p>

<pre><code>$ buster generate --domain=http://127.0.0.1:2368
</code></pre>

<p>This will generate your local site into html pages inside a new folder called "<em>static</em>".</p>

<hr />

<p>If you have followed the optional step, then you may deploy your site directly into your github repository. Input this on git bash while outside of your <em>static</em> folder:</p>

<pre><code>$ buster deploy --dir=/yourfoldernamehere/
</code></pre>

<hr />

<p>If you did not follow the optional steps, just copy and paste the contents of <em>static</em> into your repository folder and push onto GitHub.</p>

<p>Check which files have been added, open up git bash inside your repo folder.</p>

<pre><code>$ git status
$ git add -A
$ git commit -m "Commit message here"
$ git push origin gh-pages
</code></pre>

<p>This will push all of your files into the gh-pages branch of your repository. Wait a few seconds for GitHub's servers to refresh and visit your Git Pages hosted site on: <a href="http://username.github.io/">http://username.github.io/</a><strong>repositoryname</strong></p>

<p>Enjoy your new site. If you have a domain, just look up CNAME and domains on google.</p>
